{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112901/1162.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C.\nfIPAT, WOVEMBEK t>, IMT\nA-10\nPresident Goes to Farm,\nProves Fast Recovery\nContinued From First Page\nnoon and to spend the after- 1\nnoon at his own office on Capi\ntol Hill.\nDuring the morning he con\nferred with Secretary of Health,;\nEducation and, Welfare Folsom\nand Secretary of Agriculture;\nBenson on their legislative pro-;\ngrams for 1958.\nAfter the President suffered\nMonday an occlusion of a small\nbranch artery in his brain\u2014\nwhat most people would call a\nmild stroke\u2014his doctors estl-;\nmated that he would need \u201csev\neral weeks\u201d of rest and \u201csub-!\nstantially decreased activity\u201d\nfor complete recovery.\nNATO Trip Possible\nA more optimistic view on his\nrate of recovery was first indi\ncated yesterday by an an-;\nnouncement that left open the\npossibility Mr. Eisenhower still\nmay attend the NATO summit\nmeeting opening in Paris De\ncember 16\u2014something it was\ngenerally assumed his illness\nwould prevent.\nMr. Hagerty cautiously em-|\nphasized that all this does\nnot mean Mr. Eisenhower is\nfully back to normal yet\u2014just\nthat he is making excellent\nprogress.\nThose who saw the President\nat National Presbyterian\nChurch Thanksgiving services\nyesterday\u2014his first public ap\npearance since he was stricken\nMonday afternoon \u2014could see\nno signs of his illness. There\nwas nothing unusual about his\nappearance or actions. His grin\nfor news photographers was as\nbig as ever.\nLeft Up to Doctors\nThe President had disclosed\nyesterday that he and Mrs.\nEisenhower hoped to drive to\ntheir Gettysburg farm today,\nleaving the final decision to\nwhat his doctors had to say\nthis morning.\nMr. Hagerty announced at\n8:30 a m. that \"the doctors be\nlieve it is perfectly all right for\nhim to make the trip.\u201d\nMr. Hagerty read the follow\ning bulletin by Dr. Snyder:\n\u201cThe President had a good\nnight\u2019s sleep. Se slept almost\ncontinuously from early last\nevening until 6 o'clock this\nmorning. His progress con\ntinues to be excellent.\u201d\nMr. Hagerty added that the\nPresident went to bed shortly\nafter eating Thanksgiving din\nner with his family, and was\nasleep by about 8 p.m.\nAsked if Mr. Eisenhower was\novertired from his Thanksgiv\ning Day activities or whether\nthere was any other special\nreason for his going to bed so\nearly, Mr. Hagerty merely\nsmiled and said, \u201cNo.\u201d\nOnly Mr. Hagerty and Dr.\n6nyder were accompanying the\nPresident and Mrs. Eisenhower\nto Gettysburg.\nLength of Stay Indefinite\nMr. Hagerty said the Eisen\nhowers plan to stay at the\nfarm through this week end\nand that \u201cI would think\u201d their\nstay there \u201cwould extend into\nnext week.\u201d He said he would\nnot know more definitely until\ntomorrow or Sunday lust how\nmuch longer the Gettysburg\nvisit would last.\nMrs. Eisenhower plans to re\nturn to Washington no later\nthan next Wednesday.\nShe has two luncheon dates,\none on Wednesday and another\nThursday. And the White\nHouse says they still stand.\nOn Wednesday Mrs. Eisen\nhower plans luncheon with the\nWalter Reed Officers Wives\nClub at Walter Reed Medical\nCenter. The next day she has\na date to be euest of honor at\nthe Naval Officers Wives Club\nbenefit.\nMr. Hagerty did not rule out\nthe possibility that Mr. Eisen\nhower might come back to\nWashington to take part in a\ncabinet meeting and a confer\nence with a bipartisan group of\ncongressional leaders at the\nWhite House next week.\nMr. Hagerty would not say\nflatly that the President ready\nhopes to attend the Paris NATO\nmeeting next month. But that\nwas implicit in the announce\nment the press secretary read\nto newsmen yesterday.\nThat statement said the\nPresident \u201chad looked forward\u201d\nto attending the meeting and\nthat \"his doctors will decide\nlater whether he can make the\ntrip.\u201d It added that if he can\nnot go. Vice President Nixon\nwill head the United States\ndelegation.\nMr. Hagerty noted steady im\nprovement in the only symptom\nof his illness which Mr. Eisen\nhower has exhibited since he\nwent to bed with a chill Mon\nday afternoon\u2014a slight speech\ndifficulty, especially in saying\nlong words.\n\"I was not conscious of anv\nthing wrong with the speech\"\nduring a 20-minute talk with\nthe President yesterday, Mr.\nHagerty said He added that \"I\nwould not believe there would\nROULETTE\nContinued From First Page\n\u2022o her temple and pulled the\ntrigger. Police were not sure\nif anyone else had participated\nin the game, but Lt Leahy said\nthere was no doubt Mrs. Lin\ncoln was holding the gun when\nit fired.\nPolice were attempting to\ncontact Mrs. Lincoln's husband.\nDonald M. Lincoln, who they\nsaid lives in California.\nMrs. Tanner's mother is the\nwidow of Alexander McClure\nAshley, who died last summer\nafter a long career as a weather\nexpert and later as a program\nanalyst with the Department\nof Agriculture.\nBefore moving to the Mel\nrose street house, the Tanners\nlived in the same apartment\ndevelopment as Mrs Lincoln\nand Mr. Ricketts.\nPolice saiffMr. Tanner picked\nUP Mrs. Lincoln earlier in the\nday and drove her to his home\nfor dinner.\n\nbe such an improvement\u201d in\nI Mr. Eisenhower's speech as\nthere had been in only 24 hours.\nMr. Hagerty admitted he was\nsurprised at the progress.\nLater, however, he depicted\nI the President\u2019s Thanksgiving\nDay church attendance as an\ni Indication of \u201cjust exactly\nwhat the doctors have been\nsaying\u2014that his progress has\nbeen excellent.\u201d\nHis words of caution came\nwhen one newsman asked if\nthe fact that the doctors ap\nproved the visit to church\nmeant that they felt the Presi\ndent \u201cwas back to normal.\u201d\n\u201cDon\u2019t try to push or rush a\ncomplete recovery by the Pres\nident,\u201d Mr. Hagerty said. \u201cThat\nwould be an error